article.headline: Monarchs notch most lopsided win in team history
article.linkText: Shocking results: Monarchs rout slumping Detroit
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Nicole Powell made five 3-pointers and finished with a career-high 25 points, leading the Sacramento Monarchs to their most lopsided victory, 91-51 over the Detroit Shock on Sunday night.

The 40-point decision is the fourth-largest margin of victory in WNBA history and surpassed the Monarchs' team record 39-point win over Minnesota (91-52) on July 3, 2001. The largest margin of victory in league history was Houston's 45-point win over
Washington (110-65) in August 1998.

"We played outstanding, it was a great way to respond after our loss to New York," Monarchs center Yolanda Griffith said. "We played defense like we are capable of playing and we were knocking down our shots."

It was the long-range shooting of Powell that led Sacramento to its highest scoring total of the season. She scored the Monarchs' first eight points and started the second half with a 3-pointer, igniting a 17-2 run in the first five minutes that extended Sacramento's lead to 50-29.

Powell shot 10-for-17 and finished with four rebounds and three steals, helping Sacramento snap a two-game losing streak and move two games ahead of Houston in the Western Conference.

"I need to be aggressive on offense, that's something I'm trying to work on," said Powell, a second-year guard from Stanford University. "I need to work on being consistent every game. It's always good to knock down that first shot like I did tonight, but you have to do other things like rebound and play defense when your shot isn't falling."

Detroit (18-12) suffered its worst loss of the season, and the Shock have lost two straight and five of six.

The Shock, who scored their fewest points of the season, committed 24 turnovers. Detroit also lost to the Monarchs 80-63 earlier this season.

Kara Lawson scored 14 points, and Rebekkah Brunson had 11 points and a career-high 14 rebounds. Griffith had all 10 of her points in the second half as the Monarchs outscored the Shock 58-24. Ticha Penicheiro added nine assists.

Kara Braxton had 11 points and Deanna Nolan had eight for Detroit, which shot 34 percent.

"They came out and wanted the game more than us, it showed in the first five minutes [of the second half], we couldn't find the right combination of players out there," said Detroit coach Bill Laimbeer, who held a 20-minute meeting with his team following the
game.

"We have some issues that we have to solve. It comes from everybody on our team looking inside and coming to a conclusion on what we need to get done," he said.
